The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 Berlin, June 2: The German cabinet has approved a draft legislation to extend a ban on naked short selling of financial products to stem risky speculation in the financial markets, including betting on the insolvency of nations, in spite of criticism from the European Union. The decision comes two weeks after Germanys financial regulator imposed a temporary ban on short selling of sovereign bonds of euro zone countries, credit insurances on those bonds and the shares of Germanys 10 largest financial institutions.                             
	 Mumbai, June 2: Gold prices faltered today after hitting a high of Rs 18,800. Silver, however, edged up on stray industrial buying. Standard gold (99.5 purity) moved down Rs 25 per 10 grams to end at Rs 18,725 from the overnight closing of Rs 18,750. Meanwhile, the rupee has appreciated 18 paise against the dollar to close at 46.99.                             
	 New Delhi, June 2: The Supreme Court will hear the Ulip case involving Sebi and IRDA next month but may not decide who will regulate these market-linked insurance products.                             
	 Mumbai, June 2: The credit growth of banks stood at 17.96 per cent during the year ended May 21, up from 15.20 per cent a year ago. As on May 21, bank credit stood at Rs 33.24 lakh crore, the RBI said.                             
	 New Delhi, June 2: The finance ministry has said income tax payers will have to mention the receipt number of tax deducted at source forms in the returns to claim refunds from this fiscal.                            
	 New Delhi, June 2: The pan-India bid licence for broadband wireless access spectrum touched Rs 8,604 crore today, the eighth day of the auction, which translates into a revenue of Rs 25,812 crore.                            
	 New Delhi, June 2: The government may take a decision on imposing import duty on sugar in the next seven days, agriculture minister Sharad Pawar today said.
                                                                                                                          
